        category: `Other`,
        title: `Snail Poem`,
        content: `O snail, neither Hector dared your horns, nor Achilles, bright in his grief. Hercules himself, who strangled things born of darkness, would have sought relief.
My wife said so. She stood at the door with the names of the mighty and wept. I said: I know. I’ve known before. I know what the ledger has kept.
You came in spring when the field was new, you left a trail of silver on every row, we paid you in summer, the autumn too, and still the number would grow.
A snail is patient. A snail is slow. That is the whole of its povoir: it need not run, it need not show.
But snail, O great snail—O Lombard, O lord of the shell and the gate and the seal, we’ve sharpened something better than a sword: a fork.
With pepper, as is fitting. With safran, as is right. A beautiful dish, and us all sitting at a table, by good light.
Neither Hector. Neither Achilles. Neither Hercules. True, true, true. But they had monsters worth the kills. We had something better:
You.`
